---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Scattered Authorization Problem - FraiseQL Solution"
  description="How centralized compile-time authorization prevents security bugs."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>🔒 Problem: Scattered Authorization</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>How compile-time RBAC prevents authorization bugs and data leaks</strong>
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Problem: Authorization in Resolvers</h2>

      <p>
        Traditional GraphQL spreads authorization logic across resolvers:
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`// Resolver 1: Check if user is admin
const user = await getUserResolver(args);
if (!context.user.role === 'admin') {
  throw new Error('Not authorized');
}

// Resolver 2: Forgot authorization check!
const posts = await getPostsResolver(args);
// No auth check! Anyone can see all posts

// Resolver 3: Wrong authorization check
const comments = await getCommentsResolver(args);
if (context.user.id === args.user_id) {
  // Check: user can only see their own comments
  // But forgot to check if they're the post author!
}

// Resolver 4: Missing org check
const teamData = await getTeamResolver(args);
if (context.user.role === 'team_admin') {
  // Check: team admin can see data
  // But didn't verify they're admin of THIS team!
}

// Security bugs from scattered auth:
// 1. Authorization check in one resolver might be missing in another
// 2. Different checks might be inconsistent
// 3. Hard to audit: where should auth be checked?
// 4. Easy to miss edge cases (org, team, tenant, etc.)`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Why Scattered?</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Resolver per field:</strong> Each resolver implements its own auth checks
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No centralized view:</strong> Can't see all authorization rules in one place
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Easy to forget:</strong> Developer adds new field, forgets auth check
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Inconsistency:</strong> Different fields might have different auth logic
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #c41c3b;">
        <strong>Result:</strong> Authorization bugs that leak data or allow unauthorized access.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Authorization Bugs</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Bug 1: Missing Authorization Check</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Resolver chain for getting team members
resolver user.team.members():
  - Check: context.user is team_admin
  - Return members list

But developer forgot to add auth check to:
resolver user.team.budget():
  - No check! Returns sensitive budget info
  - Result: Anyone can see team budget ❌

# This is a real bug that leaked a company's financials`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Bug 2: Inconsistent Tenant Check</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# SaaS platform with multiple tenants

resolver getDocuments():
  - Check: user.tenant_id === context.user.tenant_id
  - Return documents

But forgot check in:
resolver getDocumentStats():
  - No tenant check!
  - Returns stats for ALL tenants ❌

# Result: Tenant A could see Tenant B's statistics`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Bug 3: Role-Based Access Logic Error</h3>
      <pre><code>{`resolver updateUser(user_id):
  # Check: context.user.role === 'admin'
  # But should also check: user can only update themselves
  # Exception: admin can update anyone

  if (context.user.role === 'admin') {
    // Allow update
  } else if (context.user.id === user_id) {
    // Allow self-update
  } else {
    throw 'Unauthorized'
  }

# Developer got logic backwards:
  if (context.user.role === 'admin' || context.user.id === user_id) {
    // WRONG! Non-admin users can now update admin accounts
  }

# Result: Users could escalate their own permissions ❌`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>FraiseQL Solution: Compile-Time RBAC</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>All authorization rules defined in one place, enforced at compile time:</strong>
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`# Schema-level RBAC (centralized, verified)
@fraiseql.type
class User:
    id: int
    name: str
    email: str

    # Only visible to: admin or self
    @rbac(roles=["admin"], self_access=true)
    password_hash: str

    # Only visible to: admin or same tenant
    @rbac(roles=["admin"], tenant_match=true)
    ssn: str

    # Visible to: anyone with access to this user
    profile: UserProfile

@fraiseql.type
class TeamData:
    id: int
    name: str

    # Only admin of THIS team can access
    @rbac(roles=["team_admin"], team_id_match=true)
    budget: Decimal

    # Team members can see summary, not details
    @rbac(roles=["team_admin", "team_member"], summary_only=true)
    spending_detail: SpendingDetail

# Mutations have RBAC too
@rbac(roles=["admin"])
@fraiseql.mutation
def update_user(user_id: int, name: str) -> User:
    pass

@rbac(roles=["team_admin"], team_id_match=true)
@fraiseql.mutation
def update_team_budget(team_id: int, budget: Decimal) -> TeamData:
    pass`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Compile-Time Verification</h3>
      <p>
        The compiler verifies:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Schema-level RBAC:</strong> All authorization rules defined in one place, not scattered across resolvers
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Consistency checking:</strong> Same field maintains consistent authorization rules
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Multi-tenant support:</strong> Compiler helps identify where tenant isolation should apply
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Access patterns:</strong> Centralized policy makes access patterns auditable
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p style="margin-top: 1rem; color: #059669;">
        <strong>Result:</strong> Authorization rules are centralized and verifiable, making common mistakes easier to catch during development.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Example: Healthcare Compliance</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Company:</strong> HealthData, healthcare data management platform
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Challenge:</strong> HIPAA requires field-level access control. Can't have authorization bugs.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Before (Scattered Auth): Authorization Audit Nightmare</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# 200+ resolvers, each with its own auth logic
# Compliance auditor asks: "Who can see patient SSN?"

# Search through resolvers...
# Found in 5 different places:
1. resolver getPatient() - checks: role === 'doctor'
2. resolver patientSearch() - checks: role === 'admin' (DIFFERENT!)
3. resolver exportPatientData() - NO CHECK! ❌
4. resolver updatePatientRecord() - checks: role === 'doctor' and org_id match
5. resolver patientStats() - checks: role === 'admin' OR role === 'analyst'

# Inconsistent! Auditor questions:
# - Why is exportPatientData not checked?
# - Why is patientStats different from getPatient?
# - Does analyst role need access?

# Result: HIPAA audit fails, compliance remediation costs $500K`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">After (Compile-Time RBAC): Simple Audit</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# All auth rules in one place in schema
@fraiseql.type
class PatientRecord:
    id: int
    medical_record_number: int

    @rbac(roles=["doctor", "nurse"], org_id_match=true)
    ssn: str              # Only doctors/nurses in same org

    @rbac(roles=["doctor"], org_id_match=true)
    diagnosis: str        # Only doctors

    @rbac(roles=["doctor", "pharmacist"], org_id_match=true)
    medications: str      # Doctors and pharmacists

# Compliance auditor asks: "Who can see patient SSN?"
# Answer: Open schema.json, search for "ssn"
# Answer: Roles ["doctor", "nurse"] with org_id_match

# Verification: Run compliance check
$ fraiseql compliance-audit
  ✓ All HIPAA fields protected
  ✓ No unprotected PII fields
  ✓ Organization isolation verified
  ✓ Role-based rules consistent

# Result: HIPAA audit passes easily`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Authorization Patterns</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pattern 1: Role-Based</h3>
      <pre><code>{`@rbac(roles=["admin"])
@rbac(roles=["admin", "moderator"])
@rbac(roles=["team_admin", "team_member"])`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pattern 2: Self-Access + Admin Exception</h3>
      <pre><code>{`@rbac(roles=["admin"], self_access=true)
# Means: admin can access anyone, others can access themselves`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pattern 3: Tenant/Organization Isolation</h3>
      <pre><code>{`@rbac(roles=["admin"], tenant_id_match=true)
@rbac(roles=["team_admin"], team_id_match=true)
# Means: Access only allowed if IDs match`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pattern 4: Field Redaction</h3>
      <pre><code>{`@rbac(roles=["admin", "analyst"], summary_only=true)
# Means: Role can see limited version of field`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Audit Trail Integration</h2>

      <p>
        RBAC rules automatically generate audit logs:
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`# Any access to protected field is logged
mutation UpdatePatient($id: ID!, $diagnosis: String!) {
  update_patient(id: $id, diagnosis: $diagnosis) {
    id
  }
}

# Audit log created:
{
  "timestamp": "2024-02-06T12:34:56Z",
  "user_id": "user_123",
  "user_role": "doctor",
  "action": "mutation",
  "mutation": "update_patient",
  "accessed_fields": ["diagnosis"],
  "rbac_check": {
    "field": "diagnosis",
    "required_roles": ["doctor"],
    "user_role": "doctor",
    "result": "allowed"
  }
}

# Compliance value: Prove who accessed what, when, and why`}</code></pre>
    </section>

